{"title_page": "Exchange Lifeguards", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Exchange Lifeguards\n| image          = Exchange Lifeguards.jpeg\n| image_size     =\n| caption        =\n| director       = [[Maurice Murphy (director)|Maurice Murphy]]\n| producer       = [[Phillip Avalon]]\n| writer         = Phillip Avalon\n| starring       = [[Christopher Atkins]]<br>[[Julian McMahon]]<br>[[Elliott Gould]]<br>[[Martin Cruden]]\n| music          = [[John Capek]] \n| cinematography = [[Martin McGrath (cinematographer)|Martin McGrath]] \n| editing        =\n| distributor    =\n| released       = {{Film date|1992}}\n| runtime        =\n| country        = Australia\n| language       = English\n| budget         =$1.6 million<ref name=\"phil\"/>\n| gross          = A$3,634 (Australia)<ref>[http://www.film.vic.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0004/967/AA4_Aust_Box_office_report.pdf \"Australian Films at the Australian Box Office\", ''Film Victoria''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140209075310/http://www.film.vic.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0004/967/AA4_Aust_Box_office_report.pdf |date=9 February 2014 }} accessed 12 November 2012</ref>\n}}\n[[File:WetAndWildSummerPosterSmall.jpg|thumb|upright|Movie poster in America]]\n\n'''''Exchange Lifeguards''''' is a 1992 Australian-American [[comedy film]]<ref>[http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117902087?refcatid=31&printerfriendly=true ''Exchange Lifeguards'' review at ''Variety''] accessed 9 November 2012</ref> directed by [[Maurice Murphy (director)|Maurice Murphy]] and starring [[Christopher Atkins]], [[Julian McMahon]]  and [[Elliott Gould]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Robert A. Nowlan, Gwendolyn Wright Nowlan|title=The Films of the Nineties|publisher=McFarland, 2001|isbn=0786409746}}</ref> The American title is '''''Wet and Wild Summer!'''''\n\n==Plot==\nA property developer wants to take over an Australian beach for a high rise resort. He sends his son to Australia to check out the situation, posing as an exchange lifeguard. He falls in love with a woman who owns the land his father needs for the development and finds himself sympathising with the locals.\n\n== Cast ==\n\n*[[Christopher Atkins]] as  Bobby McCain\n*[[Julian McMahon]] as Mick Dooley\n* Rebecca Carlton  as Julie Thomas\n* Vanessa Steele  as Charlene\n*[[Elliott Gould]] as Mike McCain\n*[[Richard Carter (actor)|Richard Carter]] as Al Eastman\n* Amanda Newman-Phillips  as Kylie\n* Christopher Pate  as Richard Gray\n* Lois Larimore  as Donna McCain\n* Brian M. Logan   as Terry\n*[[Mark Hembrow]] as Max\n* Peter Gow as Tishi\n* Anthony Lawrence as Clint Eastman\n* Ann Brisk  as Annie McCain\n* Rick Hochman as himself\n==Production==\nAvalon says that sales agent Dick Bateman suggested he write and produce a film set around the beach and lifeguards, with humour and a romance. Bateman said he would buy all rights for $1.5 million. Avalon wrote a script Gary Hamilton of Beyond agreed to help finance if Avalon could get Elliot Gould and Chris Atkins to star; Avalon succeeded in doing this and the film was made for $1.6 million.<ref name=\"phil\">{{cite book|first=Phil|last=Avalon|title=From Steel City to Hollywood|publisher=New Holland|year=2015|page=228}}</ref>\n== Reception ==  \nIn her review of the film  Marsha Porter describes the film as a \"vulgar Aussie version of [[Beach party film#.E2.80.9DFrankie .26 Annette.E2.80.9D|Frankie-and-Annette beach movies]]\" and as  \"sexist, badly acted, and buffoonish\".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Mick Martin, Marsha Porter|title=Video Movie Guide|publisher=Ballantine Books, 1996|isbn=0345406435|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/videomovieguide100mars}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Cinema of Australia]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0105801}}\n*[http://www.ozmovies.com.au/movie/exchange-lifeguards ''Exchange Lifeguards''] at Oz Movies\n{{Phil Avalon}}\n\n[[Category:Australian films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:1992 films]]\n[[Category:1990s thriller films]]\n[[Category:Australian thriller films]]\n\n\n{{1990s-Australia-film-stub}}\n{{1990s-thriller-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Exchange Lifeguards\n| image          = Exchange Lifeguards.jpeg\n| image_size     =\n| caption        =\n| director       = [[Maurice Murphy (director)|Maurice Murphy]]\n| producer       = [[Phillip Avalon]]\n| writer         = Phillip Avalon\n| starring       = [[Christopher Atkins]]<br>[[Julian McMahon]]<br>[[Elliott Gould]]<br>[[Martin Cruden]]\n| music          = [[John Capek]] \n| cinematography = [[Martin McGrath (cinematographer)|Martin McGrath]] \n| editing        =\n| distributor    =\n| released       = {{Film date|1992}}\n| runtime        =\n| country        = Australia\n| language       = English\n| budget         =$1.6 million<ref name=\"phil\"/>\n| gross          = A$3,634 (Australia)<ref>[http://www.film.vic.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0004/967/AA4_Aust_Box_office_report.pdf \"Australian Films at the Australian Box Office\", ''Film Victoria''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140209075310/http://www.film.vic.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0004/967/AA4_Aust_Box_office_report.pdf |date=9 February 2014 }} accessed 12 November 2012</ref>\n}}\n[[File:WetAndWildSummerPosterSmall.jpg|thumb|upright|Movie poster in America]]\n\n'''''Exchange Lifeguards''''' is a 1992 Australian-American comedy film<ref>[http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117902087?refcatid=31&printerfriendly=true ''Exchange Lifeguards'' review at ''Variety''] accessed 9 November 2012</ref> directed by [[Maurice Murphy (director)|Maurice Murphy]] and starring [[Christopher Atkins]], [[Julian McMahon]]  and [[Elliott Gould]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Robert A. Nowlan, Gwendolyn Wright Nowlan|title=The Films of the Nineties|publisher=McFarland, 2001|isbn=0786409746}}</ref> The American title is '''''Wet and Wild Summer!'''''\n\n==Plot==\nA property developer wants to take over an Australian beach for a high rise resort. He sends his son to Australia to check out the situation, posing as an exchange lifeguard. He falls in love with a woman who owns the land his father needs for the development and finds himself sympathising with the locals.\n\n== Cast ==\n\n*[[Christopher Atkins]] as  Bobby McCain\n*[[Julian McMahon]] as Mick Dooley\n* Rebecca Carlton  as Julie Thomas\n* Vanessa Steele  as Charlene\n*[[Elliott Gould]] as Mike McCain\n*[[Richard Carter (actor)|Richard Carter]] as Al Eastman\n* Amanda Newman-Phillips  as Kylie\n* Christopher Pate  as Richard Gray\n* Lois Larimore  as Donna McCain\n* Brian M. Logan   as Terry\n*[[Mark Hembrow]] as Max\n* Peter Gow as Tishi\n* Anthony Lawrence as Clint Eastman\n* Ann Brisk  as Annie McCain\n* Rick Hochman as himself\n==Production==\nAvalon says that sales agent Dick Bateman suggested he write and produce a film set around the beach and lifeguards, with humour and a romance. Bateman said he would buy all rights for $1.5 million. Avalon wrote a script Gary Hamilton of Beyond agreed to help finance if Avalon could get Elliot Gould and Chris Atkins to star; Avalon succeeded in doing this and the film was made for $1.6 million.<ref name=\"phil\">{{cite book|first=Phil|last=Avalon|title=From Steel City to Hollywood|publisher=New Holland|year=2015|page=228}}</ref>\n== Reception ==  \nIn her review of the film  Marsha Porter describes the film as a \"vulgar Aussie version of [[Beach party film#.E2.80.9DFrankie .26 Annette.E2.80.9D|Frankie-and-Annette beach movies]]\" and as  \"sexist, badly acted, and buffoonish\".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Mick Martin, Marsha Porter|title=Video Movie Guide|publisher=Ballantine Books, 1996|isbn=0345406435|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/videomovieguide100mars}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Cinema of Australia]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0105801}}\n*[http://www.ozmovies.com.au/movie/exchange-lifeguards ''Exchange Lifeguards''] at Oz Movies\n{{Phil Avalon}}\n\n[[Category:Australian films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:1992 films]]\n[[Category:1990s thriller films]]\n[[Category:Australian thriller films]]\n\n\n{{1990s-Australia-film-stub}}\n{{1990s-thriller-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exchange_Lifeguards"}
{"title_page": "Marco Branca", "text_new": "{{short description|Italian former football striker|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2012}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Marco Branca\n| image =\n| fullname = Marco Branca\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1965|1|6}}\n| birth_place = [[Grosseto]], Italy\n| height = 1.84 m\n| position = [[Forward (association football)#Striker|Striker]]\n| clubnumber =\n| youthyears1 = 1981\u20131982\n| youthyears2 = 1982\u20131984\n| youthclubs1 = [[U.S. Grosseto F.C.|Grosseto]]\n| youthclubs2 = [[Cagliari Calcio|Cagliari]]\n| years1 = 1984\u20131986\n| years2 = 1986\u20131987\n| years3 = 1987\u20131988\n| years4 = 1988\u20131990\n| years5 = 1990\u20131991\n| years6 = 1991\u20131992\n| years7 = 1992\u20131994\n| years8 = 1994\u20131995\n| years9 = 1995\u20131996\n| years10 = 1996\u20131998\n| years11 = 1998\u20131999\n| years12 = 1999\u20132000\n| years13 = 2000\u20132001\n| clubs1 = [[Cagliari Calcio|Cagliari]]\n| clubs2 = [[Udinese Calcio|Udinese]]\n| clubs3 = [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]]\n| clubs4 = [[Udinese Calcio|Udinese]]\n| clubs5 = [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]]\n| clubs6 = [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]]\n| clubs7 = [[Udinese Calcio|Udinese]]\n| clubs8 = [[Parma F.C.|Parma]]\n| clubs9 = [[A.S. Roma|Roma]]\n| clubs10 = [[F.C. Internazionale Milano|Internazionale]]\n| clubs11 = [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]]\n| clubs12 = [[FC Luzern]]\n| clubs13 = [[A.C. Monza Brianza 1912|Monza]]\n| caps1 = 52\n| goals1 = 4\n| caps2 = 18\n| goals2 = 2\n| caps3 = 9\n| goals3 = 1\n| caps4 = 55\n| goals4 = 13\n| caps5 = 20\n| goals5 = 5\n| caps6 = 23\n| goals6 = 5\n| caps7 = 58\n| goals7 = 22\n| caps8 = 25\n| goals8 = 7\n| caps9 = 7\n| goals9 = 2\n| caps10 = 52\n| goals10 = 23\n| caps11 = 12\n| goals11 = 9\n| caps12 = 10\n| goals12 = 2\n| caps13 = 17\n| goals13 = 7\n| totalcaps = 348\n| totalgoals = 102\n| nationalyears1 = 1996\n| nationalteam1 = [[Italy national football team|Italy Olympic]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 3\n| nationalgoals1 = 4\n| manageryears1 =\n| managerclubs1 =\n}}\n'''Marco Branca''' (born 6 January 1965) is an Italian former professional [[association football|football]] [[Forward (association football)#Striker|striker]] who was, until February 2014, [[sporting director]] of [[Serie A]] club [[Internazionale]].\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Early career===\nBorn in [[Grosseto]], Branca started his playing career with [[U.S. Grosseto F.C.|Grosseto]], the then-amateur local team of his native city, but was soon signed by [[Cagliari Calcio|Cagliari]], where he made his professional debut. He then moved to [[Udinese Calcio|Udinese]], [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]] and then again to Udinese. Following another season with Sampdoria, he signed first for [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]] and then for [[Parma F.C.|Parma]]. In 1995, he transferred to [[A.S. Roma]], who sold him in the 1996 winter transfer window to [[F.C. Internazionale Milano|Internazionale]] in exchange for [[Marco Delvecchio]].\n\n===Internazionale and Middlesbrough===\nIn his first season with the Nerazzuri, Branca scored an impressive 17 goals in 24 matches, but did not repeat in his next campaign and was sold to English second-tier side [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]]. Branca scored nine goals in 12 league games for Middlesbrough, including two on his league debut in a 3\u20131 victory against [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]], a [[hat-trick]] versus [[Bury F.C.|Bury]] and another two in the 6\u20130 win over [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]]. In addition, he played two [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] games, scoring the second goal against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in the semi-final second leg on his debut.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-merson-and-branca-light-boros-way-1145724.html |title=Merson and Branca light Boro's way |publisher=[[The Independent]] |date=18 February 1998 |accessdate=12 November 2009 | location=London | first=Ian | last=Potts}}</ref> His nine goals aided in Boro's promotion to the Premiership, but he was then sold to Swiss club [[FC Luzern]].\n\n===Later career===\nBranca saw out his playing days with FC Luzern and Italian lower-league club Monza before retiring in 2001.\n\n==International career==\nBranca was a member of the [[Italy national under-21 football team|Italy under-21 side]] that won the [[1996 UEFA European Under-21 Championship]]; he also took part at the [[Football at the 1996 Summer Olympics|1996 Summer Olympics]] that year.\n\n==Management career==\nFrom 2002 until February 2014,<ref>http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1953026-inter-milan-fire-technical-director-marco-branca</ref> Branca was part of [[F.C. Internazionale Milano|Internazionale]]'s management, working in their transfer network. He helped organise the transfers of [[L\u00facio]], [[Diego Milito]], [[Thiago Motta]], [[Wesley Sneijder]] and [[Samuel Eto'o]].\n\n==Honours==\n===Club===\n'''Parma'''\n* [[UEFA Cup]]: [[1994\u201395 UEFA Cup|1994\u201395]]\n\n===International===\n'''Italy under-21'''\n* [[UEFA European Under-21 Football Championship]]: [[1996 UEFA European Under-21 Football Championship|1996]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070927020153/http://www.footballplus.com/players/7130/Marco-Branca.html Playing career]\n{{Italy Squad 1996 Summer Olympics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Branca, Marco}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Grosseto]]\n[[Category:Italian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Cagliari Calcio players]]\n[[Category:A.C. Monza players]]\n[[Category:Udinese Calcio players]]\n[[Category:ACF Fiorentina players]]\n[[Category:U.C. Sampdoria players]]\n[[Category:A.S. Roma players]]\n[[Category:Parma Calcio 1913 players]]\n[[Category:Inter Milan players]]\n[[Category:Middlesbrough F.C. players]]\n[[Category:FC Luzern players]]\n[[Category:Serie A players]]\n[[Category:Serie B players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Swiss Super League players]]\n[[Category:Footballers at the 1996 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic footballers of Italy]]\n[[Category:Italian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Italian expatriate sportspeople in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Italian expatriate sportspeople in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:UEFA Cup winning players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Italian former football striker|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2012}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Marco Branca\n| image =\n| fullname = Marco Branca\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1965|1|6}}\n| birth_place = [[Grosseto]], [[Italy]]\n| height = {{convert|1.84|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}}\n| position = [[Forward (association football)#Striker|Striker]]\n| clubnumber =\n| youthyears1 = 1981\u20131982 | youthyears2 =1982\u20131984\n| youthclubs1 = [[U.S. Grosseto F.C.|Grosseto]] | youthclubs2 =[[Cagliari Calcio|Cagliari]]\n| years1 = 1984\u20131986 | years2 = 1986\u20131987 | years3 = 1987\u20131988 | years4 = 1988\u20131990 | years5 = 1990\u20131991 | years6 = 1991\u20131992 | years7 = 1992\u20131994 | years8 = 1994\u20131995 | years9 = 1995\u20131996 | years10 = 1996\u20131998 | years11 = 1998\u20131999 | years12 = 1999\u20132000 | years13 =2000\u20132001\n| clubs1 = [[Cagliari Calcio|Cagliari]] | clubs2 = [[Udinese Calcio|Udinese]] | clubs3 = [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]] | clubs4 = [[Udinese Calcio|Udinese]] | clubs5 = [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]] | clubs6 = [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]] | clubs7 = [[Udinese Calcio|Udinese]] | clubs8 = [[Parma F.C.|Parma]] | clubs9 = [[A.S. Roma|Roma]] | clubs10 = [[F.C. Internazionale Milano|Internazionale]] | clubs11 = [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] | clubs12 = [[FC Luzern]] | clubs13 =[[A.C. Monza Brianza 1912|Monza]]\n| caps1 = 52 | goals1 = 4 | caps2 = 18 | goals2 = 2 | caps3 = 9 | goals3 = 1 | caps4 = 55 | goals4 = 13 | caps5 = 20 | goals5 = 5 | caps6 = 23 | goals6 = 5 | caps7 = 58 | goals7 = 22 | caps8 = 25 | goals8 = 7 | caps9 = 7 | goals9 = 2 | caps10 = 52 | goals10 = 23 | caps11 = 12 | goals11 = 9 | caps12 = 10 | goals12 = 2 | caps13 = 17 | goals13 = 7\n| totalcaps = 348\n| totalgoals = 102\n| nationalyears1= 1996\n| nationalteam1= [[Italy national football team|Italy Olympic]]\n| nationalcaps1= 3 | nationalgoals1 = 4\n| manageryears1=\n| managerclubs1=\n}}\n'''Marco Branca''' (born 6 January 1965 in [[Grosseto]]) is an [[Italy|Italian]] former [[Football (soccer)|football]] [[Forward (association football)#Striker|striker]] who was, until February 2014, [[sporting director]] of [[Serie A]] club [[Internazionale]].\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Early career===\nBranca started his playing career with the then-amateur local team of his native city [[U.S. Grosseto F.C.|Grosseto]], but was soon signed by [[Cagliari Calcio|Cagliari]], where he made his professional debut. He then moved to [[Udinese Calcio|Udinese]], [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]] and then again to Udinese. Following another season with Sampdoria, he signed first for [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]] and then for [[Parma F.C.|Parma]]. In 1995, he transferred to [[A.S. Roma]], who sold him in the 1996 winter transfer window to [[F.C. Internazionale Milano|Internazionale]] in exchange for [[Marco Delvecchio]].\n\n===Internazionale and Middlesbrough===\nIn his first season with the Nerazzuri, Branca scored an impressive 17 goals in 24 matches, but did not repeat in his next campaign and was sold to English second-tier side [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]]. Branca scored nine goals in 12 league games for Middlesbrough, including two on his league debut in a 3\u20131 victory against [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]], a [[hat-trick]] versus [[Bury F.C.|Bury]] and another two in the 6\u20130 win over [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]]. In addition, he played two [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] games, scoring the second goal against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in the semi-final second leg on his debut.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-merson-and-branca-light-boros-way-1145724.html |title=Merson and Branca light Boro's way |publisher=[[The Independent]] |date=18 February 1998 |accessdate=12 November 2009 | location=London | first=Ian | last=Potts}}</ref> His nine goals aided in Boro's promotion to the Premiership, but he was then sold to Swiss club [[FC Luzern]].\n\n===Later career===\nBranca saw out his playing days with FC Luzern and Italian lower-league club Monza before retiring in 2001.\n\n==International career==\nBranca was a member of the [[Italy national under-21 football team|Italy under-21 side]] that won the [[1996 UEFA European Under-21 Championship]]; he also took part at the [[Football at the 1996 Summer Olympics|1996 Summer Olympics]] that year.\n\n==Management career==\nFrom 2002 until February 2014,<ref>http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1953026-inter-milan-fire-technical-director-marco-branca</ref> Branca was part of [[F.C. Internazionale Milano|Internazionale]]'s management, working in their transfer network. He helped organise the transfers of [[L\u00facio]], [[Diego Milito]], [[Thiago Motta]], [[Wesley Sneijder]] and [[Samuel Eto'o]].\n\n==Honours==\n===Club===\n;Parma\n* [[UEFA Cup]] winner: [[1994\u201395 UEFA Cup|1994\u201395]].\n\n===International===\n;Italy under-21\n* [[UEFA European Under-21 Football Championship]] winner: [[1996 UEFA European Under-21 Football Championship|1996]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070927020153/http://www.footballplus.com/players/7130/Marco-Branca.html Playing career]\n{{Italy Squad 1996 Summer Olympics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Branca, Marco}}\n[[Category:People from Grosseto]]\n[[Category:Italian footballers]]\n[[Category:Cagliari Calcio players]]\n[[Category:A.C. Monza players]]\n[[Category:Udinese Ca